{"id":12240,"date":"2022-03-14T21:06:00","date_gmt":"2022-03-14T21:06:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/?p=12240"},"modified":"2022-06-14T21:12:46","modified_gmt":"2022-06-14T21:12:46","slug":"accessibilityforableds","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/accessibilityforableds\/","title":{"rendered":"#AccessibilityForAbleds"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<div class=\"wp-container-3 wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-container-1 wp-block-column\">\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-twitter wp-block-embed-twitter\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\n<blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\" data-width=\"550\" data-dnt=\"true\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">We are all talking about how it feels to see ableds accommodating themselves with the the accessibility that we disabled people fight for every day, all because of <a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/hashtag\/COVID%E3%83%BC19?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">#COVID\u30fc19<\/a>. <br><br>Let&#39;s use the hashtag <a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/hashtag\/AccessiblilityForAbleds?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">#AccessiblilityForAbleds<\/a> when we talk about this. I want to hear your thoughts!<\/p>&mdash; Kate\u267f (@KateMcWilli) <a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/KateMcWilli\/status\/1236440655095689216?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">March 7, 2020<\/a><\/blockquote><script async src=\"https:\/\/platform.twitter.com\/widgets.js\" charset=\"utf-8\"><\/script>\n<\/div><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-container-2 wp-block-column\">\n<p>On March 7, 2020, as North American cities began to respond to the pandemic with remote school and work options, Canadian disability activist Kate McWilliams created the hashtag <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/KateMcWilli\/status\/1236440655095689216\" target=\"_blank\">#AccessibilityForAbleds<\/a>. The pandemic revealed how easy it was to provide certain accommodations\u00a0that disabled and chronically ill people had been demanding, unsuccessfully, for years.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2014Mara Mills<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>On March 7, 2020, as North American cities began to respond to the pandemic with remote school and work options, Canadian disability activist Kate McWilliams created the hashtag #AccessibilityForAbleds. The pandemic revealed how easy it was to provide certain accommodations\u00a0that disabled and chronically ill people had been demanding, unsuccessfully, for&hellip; <a class=\"continue\" href=\"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/accessibilityforableds\/\">Continue Reading<span> #AccessibilityForAbleds<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":12241,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"advanced_seo_description":"","jetpack_seo_html_title":"","jetpack_seo_noindex":false,"_FSMCFIC_featured_image_caption":"","_FSMCFIC_featured_image_nocaption":"","_FSMCFIC_featured_image_hide":""},"categories":[44],"tags":[],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/06\/Accessibility-for-ableds.jpg?fit=1192%2C652&ssl=1","jetpack_sharing_enabled":true,"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/12240"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=12240"}],"version-history":[{"count":3,"href":"https:\/\/disabilitycovidchronicles.nyu.edu\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/12240\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version